    Knowledge of linguistic subjectivity could enhance the abilities of such systems to recognize and generate expressions referring to such states of affairs in natural text.
  
  
    Knowledge of subjective language promises to be beneficial for many NLP applications including information extraction, question answering, text categorization, and summarization.
    This article has presented the results of an empirical study in acquiring knowledge of subjective language from corpora in which a number of feature types were learned and evaluated on different types of data with positive results.
    We showed that unique words are subjective more often than expected and that unique words are valuable clues to subjectivity.
    We also presented a procedure for automatically identifying potentially subjective collocations, including fixed collocations and collocations with placeholders for unique words.
